216. concinnamt. Concinnare is a favourite colloquial word sor ‘working up’ anything. Here it is ‘has worked up in readiness,’ i.e. ‘has prepared.’ Rud. 96 con- cinnem lutum, Men. 102 tantas struices concinnat patinarias. ibid. 739 quam (pallam) mihi dedit alia mulier, ut concinnandam darem.

217. aues adsuescunt. It will be agreed that adsuesco here and consuesco in v. 222 must both be taken as verbs neuter or verbs active. The translation ‘the birds become familiarised' is unobjec- tionable here, though it involves a change of subject. But in v. 222 ‘they become familiarised’ with bene salutando &v- is not so suit- able. Ussing however so takes it. But see Munro's note on Lucr. 1v. 1282 where examples of com- pounds of suesco used transitively are quoted, e.g. Hor. Sat. 1. 4. 105 insueuit pater optimus hoc me, ibid. 11. 2. 109 adsuerit mentem corpusque superbum. On the whole I should prefer to take both verbs as transitives here with aucupes, i.e. lenones as subj. and aues, i.e. amatores, as object.

219. rem soluont aucupi, ‘they recoup the sowler.’ Cf. v. 321, v. 454, Cure. 553 tibi res soluta est recte, Pseud. 6 30. and Livy vt. 14. 5 rem creditori palam populo soluit, quoted by Ussing.
